title: The Blue Jays try to keep the series going in game 5 of the ALCS
text: Toronto Blue Jays first baseman Chris Colabello and fans try for a foul ball during the third inning in Game 5 of baseball's American League Championship Series against the Kansas City Royals on Wednesday, Oct. 21, 2015, in Toronto.(Paul Sancya/The Associated Press) Toronto Blue Jays starting pitcher Marco Estrada throws during the first inning of game five of the American League Championship Series Oct 21, 2015 in Toronto.(Mark Blinch for The Globe and Mail) Kansas City Royals' Lorenzo Cain, right, reacts after striking out against the Toronto Blue Jays during the first inning in Game 5 of baseball's American League Championship Series on Wednesday, Oct. 21, 2015, in Toronto.(Matt Slocum/The Associated Press) Fans cheer as Toronto Blue Jays starting pitcher Marco Estrada winds up during the first inning of game five of the American League Championship Series Oct 21, 2015 in Toronto.(Mark Blinch for The Globe and Mail) Fans cheer before the start of Game 5 of baseball's American League Championship Series between the Kansas City Royals and the Toronto Blue Jays on Wednesday, Oct. 21, 2015, in Toronto.(Matt Slocum/The Associated Press) Kansas City Royals right fielder Paulo Orlando signs autographs before Game 5 of baseball's American League Championship Series against the Toronto Blue Jays on Wednesday, Oct. 21, 2015, in Toronto.(Charlie Riedel/The Associated Press) Young fans watch during batting practice before Game 5 of baseball's American League Championship Series between the Kansas City Royals and the Toronto Blue Jays on Wednesday, Oct. 21, 2015, in Toronto.(Paul Sancya/The Associated Press) Josh Donaldson #20 of the Toronto Blue Jays reacts prior to game five of the American League Championship Series between the Toronto Blue Jays and the Kansas City Royals at Rogers Centre on October 21, 2015 in Toronto, Canada.(Harry How/Getty Images)
